The 1990 Annual Report of Stichting Lobi (Love Foundation), the Family Planning Association of Suriname, has information about the demographic, health, and family planning background of Suriname, history and philosophy of the organization, long-term objectives, strategies, current projects and special activities, with photographs. Since its founding in 1968, with major support from Dutch Development Aid, Lobi has opened 2 clinics, provided Pap smears, mounted education and mass media campaigns including a pop record in Surinamese and a sex education book for youths, conducted a KAP survey and an AIDS education campaign. Lobi was one of the founding members of the Caribbean Family Planning Affiliation in 1971, and joined the IPPF in 1990. Suriname gained independence from the Netherlands in 1975. The country is composed of 37% East Indians, 31% Creoles, 15% Javanese and 1% Europeans. 75% of the people live in the capital, Paramaribo. The infant mortality rate is 29.4/1000, the maternal mortality, 6.7/1000, life expectancy is 66.6 years. There is no official government family planning policy, but the government cooperates with the family planning association in providing services in its clinics. The long term objective is to improve quality of life and dignity of the family by improving the health of women and children. The main strategies are to persuade the government to provide family planning and sex education; to develop special education and motivation programs for target groups; and to provide clinical services. A project recently completed was a survey of single and married men: both stated that the main aim of contraception is to allow women to be independent and to give men the opportunity to have several partners.

Antigens and antigen presentation in relation to vaccine development /

Classification and analysis of antigens for development of vaccines are reviewed. Of the 50 vaccines currently used in human and veterinary medicine, the most successful are live and attenuated viral antigens. Most attenuated virus are effective and long-lasting after a single dose, but may inactivated whole and subunit vaccines require multidoses. Bacterial vaccines include the attenuated BCG vaccine, less effective inactivated whole vaccines, and several subunit and toxoid vaccines. New approaches to vaccine development take into account knowledge of T and B cell dynamics. Both types of lymphocytes recognize epitopes of 6-8 amino acids or 4-5 sugars. B cells recognize intact antigens with a tertiary or quaternary shape on the Ig receptors at the B cell surface, but T cells recognize a major histocompatibility-peptide complex with a hydrophobic region at the surface of an antigen-presenting cell. New possibilities for antigens include synthetic antigens (only in research stages), antigens produced through recombinant DNA (e.g., hepatitis B made in yeast, and several veterinary vaccines made in E. coli), recombinant live vectors (e.g., vaccinia, adenovirus, BCG, Salmonella). anti-idiotype antigens are theoretically possible and have been attempted with poliovirus type II and rabies. New developments such as gene banks and monoclonal antibodies have greatly facilitated identification and isolation of candidates for vaccine antigens. Ways to enhance the immunogenicity of simple antigens include new adjuvants, controlled release formulations, and recruitment of T-cells to help activate antigen-presenting cells. Finally, new routes of administration will appear based on new knowledge of lymphocyte circulation. Examples are oral administration of adenovirus vaccine, a virus that infects the respiratory tract, and the potential use of the oral route for organisms that infect the genital tract.

Assessment of three types of spaceflight hardware for tissue culture studies :
comparison of skeletal tissue growth and differentiation /

The BioProcessing Module (BPM), Materials Dispersion Apparatus (MDA), and Fluid Processing Apparatus (FPA) were assessed for their ability to support tissue culture during space flight. Tissue used in the experiments was cultured mouse pre-metatarsal mesenchyme. Tissue analysis examined measurement of the length of the cartilage rods, detection of mineralized tissue, and observation of terminally differentiated chondrocytes. Only the rods grown in the FPA showed consistently longer growth in length and none of the systems supported cell differentiation or mineralization.
